  "prompt": "Why don't Google merged Allo and Duo to make one single app?",
  "response": "Google originally launched Allo and Duo as separate apps with distinct purposes: Allo was a messaging app with smart features, while Duo was a video calling app. Over time, Google shifted its strategy to streamline its communication services, leading to the discontinuation of Allo and the focus on Duo and Messages (SMS, RCS, and chat).\n\nHere are some reasons why Google didn\u2019t merge Allo and Duo into a single app:\n\n1. **Different Core Functionalities**: Allo was primarily for text messaging with AI-powered features, while Duo was designed for video calls. Merging them might have resulted in a bloated app that didn\u2019t excel in either area.\n\n2. **Market Positioning**: Google wanted Duo to compete with apps like FaceTime by focusing solely on high-quality video calling, while Allo was aimed at competing with WhatsApp for messaging.\n\n3. **User Experience**: Keeping the apps separate allowed users to choose the service that best fit their needs without unnecessary complexity.\n\n4. **Strategic Shift**: Google eventually shifted its focus to RCS (Rich Communication Services) through Google Messages and reinforced Duo as its primary video calling app. This made Allo redundant.\n\n5. **Fragmentation Concerns**: Google has a history of launching and discontinuing apps, and merging Allo and Duo might not have resolved the fragmentation issue in its communication ecosystem. Instead, Google chose to simplify and consolidate its offerings.\n\nIn the end, Google decided to phase out Allo (in 2019) and enhance Duo with features like group calling and integration with Google Meet, while Messages became the primary platform for text-based communication in Android. This approach aligns with Google\u2019s goal of providing more focused and streamlined services.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
